  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through various international organizations and agreements. Here are some of the key ones:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**:\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization founded in 1989 to develop policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - It sets international standards known as the FATF Recommendations, which are widely recognized as the global benchmark for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This was one of the first international efforts to combat money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention includes measures to prevent and combat money laundering, particularly in the context of corruption.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) that member states are required to implement into their national laws. These directives aim to harmonize AML measures across the EU and are regularly updated to address emerging risks.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines and principles for banks to follow in order to prevent money laundering. While these are not legally binding, they are widely adopted by financial institutions globally.\n\n5. **Wolfsberg Group**:\n   - The Wolfsberg Group is an association of global banks that has developed a set of anti-money laundering principles, particularly for private banking. These principles are widely followed by financial institutions.\n\n6. **Egmont Group**:\n   - The Egmont Group is a network of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) around the world that collaborate to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n7. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**:\n   - Both the IMF and the World Bank provide technical assistance and conduct assessments to help countries implement effective AML and CFT measures.\n\nThese international frameworks and laws are complemented by national laws and regulations that individual countries implement to align with international standards and to address specific domestic issues related to money laundering.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
